━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 1. ACTUAL BUGS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

[BUG-01] stripToolPatterns exists in 3 different places with 3 different implementations
  Files:
    - src/main/ipc/shared-utils.js:1-54  (character-by-character state machine, correct)
    - src/main/tool-chain-controller.js:77-112  (String.replace with \x00 placeholders, buggy)
    - src/main/agent-loop.js:319-322  (naive regex, doesn't handle nested braces at all)
  
  Bug in tool-chain-controller.js:79:
    The `.replace()` callback receives (match, offset) but tries to use
    the outer `text` variable to scan ahead. The problem: `.replace()`
    doesn't support "consume more characters than the match" — it replaces
    only the matched substring, so the \x00 placeholder hack inserts
    NUL chars for the JSON body length, but the *match itself* is still
    only the `TOOL:name{` prefix. The actual JSON body remains in the
    string and only gets removed if the \x00 count is exactly right.
    Edge cases with unicode multi-byte chars will miscalculate the count.

  Bug in agent-loop.js:321:
    `/TOOL:\w+\{[^}]*\}/g` doesn't handle nested braces. A tool call
    like `TOOL:run_command{"cmd":"echo {hello}"}` will leave `"}` behind
    because the regex stops at the first `}`.

  Fix: Use ONE canonical implementation. shared-utils.js has the correct
  one — import it everywhere.


[BUG-02] deleteAgent() in agent-manager.js does nothing with the fetched agent
  File: src/main/agent-manager.js:186-188
    async deleteAgent(id) {
        const agent = await this.db.getAgent(id);
        if (agent) {}  // ← empty block, no cleanup
        return await this.db.deleteAgent(id);
    }
  Meanwhile, the IPC handler in register-agent-system-handlers.js:249-257
  does call `toolPermissionService.deleteAgentProfile(id)` AFTER
  agentManager.deleteAgent(). But agent folder, agent sessions, and
  subagent runs for that agent are never cleaned up.
  
  So deleting an agent leaves:
    - Orphaned folder in agentin/agents/pro/<slug>/
    - Orphaned chat_sessions rows with agent_id = <deleted id>
    - Orphaned subagent_runs rows
  

[BUG-03] getConversations() ignores the `limit` parameter when sessionId is provided
  File: src/main/database.js:136-146
    async getConversations(limit = 100, sessionId = null) {
        if (sessionId) {
            return this.all('SELECT * FROM conversations WHERE session_id = ? ORDER BY timestamp', [sessionId]);
            // ← limit is completely ignored!
        }
        // ... also ignored in the second branch
    }
  Every caller passes a limit (20, 60, 100) but it's never applied.
  For long sessions this loads the ENTIRE history into memory.


[BUG-04] `connectors:delete` handler re-requires fs and path inside the handler
  File: src/main/ipc/register-agent-system-handlers.js:191-199
    ipcMain.handle('connectors:delete', async (event, name) => {
        // ...
        const fs = require('fs');    // ← already imported at top of file (line 1)
        const path = require('path'); // ← already imported at top of file (line 2)
    });
  Not a crash, but it shows copy-paste origin. The inner `require` shadows
  the outer one — works fine but adds confusion.


[BUG-05] llm:fetch-qwen-oauth also re-requires os, fs, path inside the handler
  File: src/main/ipc/register-llm-handlers.js:541-543
    const os = require('os');
    const fs = require('fs');
    const path = require('path');
  Same pattern — these are already available in the outer scope.


[BUG-06] _lockMode / _lockPreemptible on InferenceDispatcher is global but overwritten per call
  File: src/main/inference-dispatcher.js:25-26, 123-124, 151-153
  If two dispatches run concurrently (parallel lanes), the second call
  overwrites `this._lockMode` and `this._lockPreemptible` set by the
  first. The `finally` block then clears them to null even while the
  first call is still running. Any code checking these fields mid-flight
  gets stale or wrong values.


[BUG-07] updateCustomTool doesn't update `code` or `input_schema` columns
  File: src/main/database.js:427-429
    this.run(
        'UPDATE custom_tools SET name = ?, description = ? WHERE name = ?',
        [nextName, nextDescription, existingName]
    );
  The UPDATE only sets `name` and `description`. If a user edits the
  tool's code or input_schema through the UI, those changes are silently
  dropped. The IPC handler (register-tools-capability-handlers.js:160-163)
  re-registers the tool in memory with the new code, but it's never persisted
  to the database — so a restart loses the edit.


[BUG-08] addPromptRule always returns `active: false` regardless of DB default
  File: src/main/database.js:181-188
    async addPromptRule(rule) {
        const { name, content, type = 'rule' } = rule;
        // INSERT doesn't include `active` column — DB default is used
        const result = this.run(...);
        return { ...rule, id: result.id, active: false };
        // ← hardcodes false, ignores DB schema default
    }
  If the DB default for `active` is 1 (true), the return value lies.
  Callers get `active: false` while the DB has `active: 1`.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 2. OVERPROTECTION / REDUNDANT CODE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

[OVER-01] setSetting() and saveSetting() are identical twins
  File: src/main/database.js:304-317
  Both do: INSERT OR REPLACE INTO settings (key, value) VALUES (?, ?)
  Some callers use setSetting, some use saveSetting. It's confusing.
  Within the same file: line 213 calls setSetting, line 367 calls saveSetting.
  Fix: Keep one, alias the other → `saveSetting = setSetting`.


[OVER-02] Every DB method is async but none do async work (REVISED — intentional interface)
  File: src/main/database.js (entire file)
  `better-sqlite3` is 100% synchronous. Every method wraps sync calls in `async`.
  REVISED ANALYSIS: This is a forward-compatible interface decision. The app already
  has a Docker headless mode (docker-entry.js) and may move to a different DB backend
  (e.g., SQLite with WAL over async I/O, or a networked DB for multi-user). Making
  the interface async now means callers don't need to change when the backend does.
  The Promise overhead per call is negligible (~0.01ms per microtask).
  Severity: LOW (style preference, not a bug)
  Kept as a note — but this is a reasonable design choice, not overprotection.


[OVER-03] Triple session-type check pattern repeated ~15 times
  File: src/main/ipc/register-chat-data-handlers.js
  Almost every IPC handler does:
    if (isPrivateSessionId(sessionId) && privateSessionStore) { ... }
    if (testClientMode && isTestSessionId(sessionId)) { ... }
    // normal path
  
  This 3-branch pattern is copy-pasted across: get-conversations,
  add-conversation, clear-conversations, create-chat-session,
  load-chat-session, clear-chat-session, switch-chat-session,
  delete-chat-session, delete-all-conversations, send-message,
  interpret-tool-result, get-session-artifacts, read-session-artifact,
  write-session-artifact.

  Fix: Extract a session-type dispatcher:
    function withSession(sessionId, { onPrivate, onTest, onNormal })


[OVER-04] Unused `options = {}` parameter in many IPC handlers (REVISED — extensibility pattern)
  Files: src/main/ipc/register-agent-system-handlers.js
  Many handlers accept `options = {}` but never read it. (20 handlers listed.)
  REVISED ANALYSIS: This is a forward-compatible API pattern. The IPC handlers are
  called via HeadlessIpcBridge in Docker/external-test modes, and may be called by
  future A2A protocol adapters or connector scripts. Adding `options` now means new
  callers can pass context (e.g., `{ actor: 'a2a', requestId: '...' }`) without
  changing the handler signature. The pattern is used consistently and costs nothing.
  Severity: LOW (intentional, not dead code)
  Recommendation: Add a one-line JSDoc comment to one handler explaining the pattern,
  so future contributors know it's intentional.


[OVER-05] execute-tool and execute-mcp-tool are nearly identical handlers (REVISED)
  File: src/main/ipc/register-tools-capability-handlers.js:10-57
  Both call `mcpServer.executeTool(toolName, params)`. The difference:
  execute-mcp-tool also checks `result.needsPermission`.
  REVISED ANALYSIS: execute-tool is the basic path used by workflow runner and
  internal callers. execute-mcp-tool is the UI-facing path that adds permission
  checks. The split is intentional — internal callers (daemon, subtask runtime)
  should bypass permission dialogs. This is a trust-level separation, not duplication.
  Severity: LOW (intentional, but the naming is confusing)
  Similarly: get-ai-providers vs get-providers and getProviderModels vs get-models
  may serve different callers (renderer vs external API). Audit before removing.


[OVER-06] getAgentFolderPathById() always returns null
  File: src/main/agent-manager.js:334-336
    getAgentFolderPathById(id) {
        return null;
    }
  Dead method. Either implement it or remove it.


[OVER-07] isEchoingResult() defined but never called
  File: src/main/tool-chain-controller.js:553-571
  The method exists with full JSDoc but no caller anywhere in the codebase.


[OVER-08] Overly defensive string coercion patterns
  Files: Many
  Pattern like `String(value || '').trim().toLowerCase()` appears 50+ times.
  In many cases the value is already guaranteed to be a string (e.g., it
  comes from a DB column that's TEXT, or from a JSON property just parsed).
  
  Example from inference-dispatcher.js:53:
    const provider = String(options.provider || this.aiService.getCurrentProvider() || 'ollama')
        .trim().toLowerCase() || 'ollama';
  This has TWO fallbacks to 'ollama' — one inside String(), one outside.
  If String() returns empty after trim, the outer || catches it. But
  getCurrentProvider() already returns a non-empty string, so the second
  fallback is dead code.


[OVER-09] Redundant `fs.existsSync` before `fs.statSync` / `fs.readFileSync`
  Files: Many (agent-manager.js, background-memory-daemon.js, plugin-manager.js)
  Pattern: if (fs.existsSync(path)) { fs.readFileSync(path) }
  This is a TOCTOU pattern (time-of-check to time-of-use) and doubles
  the filesystem calls. Better: just try/catch the readFileSync.


[OVER-10] dispatchOptions built with 7 individual `if` checks instead of spread
  File: src/main/tool-chain-controller.js:236-262
    if (options.includeTools !== undefined) {
        dispatchOptions.includeTools = options.includeTools;
    }
    if (options.includeRules !== undefined) {
        dispatchOptions.includeRules = options.includeRules;
    }
    // ... 5 more identical patterns
  
  Could be: const dispatchOptions = { mode, sessionId, agentId,
    ...pick(options, ['includeTools','includeRules','includeEnv', ...]) };


