 5. SYNTAX & STYLE INCONSISTENCIES
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

[STYLE-01] Mixed line endings within single files
  Files like database.js, tool-chain-controller.js, connector-runtime.js
  have mixed CRLF (\r\n) and LF (\n) within the same file. Often the
  original code is CRLF and later additions are LF. This creates noisy
  diffs and can cause issues with some tools.
  Fix: Add .editorconfig and .gitattributes, then normalize.

[STYLE-02] Inconsistent indentation in mcp-server.js
  File: src/main/mcp-server.js:99-101
    setSessionWorkspace(sessionWorkspace) {
      this._sessionWorkspace = sessionWorkspace;    // ← 6-space indent
    }
  While every other method in the class uses 4-space indent. This is
  visually jarring in the middle of the file.

[STYLE-03] Inconsistent error return patterns
  Across IPC handlers, errors are returned in 3 different formats:
    1. return { error: 'message' }                    // agent-memory handlers
    2. return { success: false, error: 'message' }    // task-queue handlers
    3. throw error                                    // agent CRUD handlers
  
  The renderer has to handle all 3 patterns. This is a maintenance hazard.
  Fix: Pick ONE error contract and apply it everywhere.

[STYLE-04] console.log left in production-facing IPC handlers
  File: src/main/ipc/register-tools-capability-handlers.js:24-27
    ipcMain.handle('activate-tool-group', async (event, groupId) => {
        console.log('[IPC] activate-tool-group called with:', groupId);
        // ...
        console.log('[IPC] Group activated successfully:', result);
    });
  File: src/main/ipc/register-llm-handlers.js:418
    console.log('llm:get-models called with provider:', provider, ...);
  File: register-llm-handlers.js:472
    console.log('Saving config:', nextConfig);  // logs entire config object
  
  These log on every user interaction. In production this creates a lot
  of noise and potentially leaks config data to the console.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
 6. THINGS THAT LOOK WRONG BUT AREN'T (no action needed)
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

[OK-01] maxChainSteps = Number.POSITIVE_INFINITY
  Looks scary but _resolveMaxChainSteps() checks DB setting first and
  only falls through to this if the setting is missing. In practice,
  the setting is always present after baseinit. Acceptable for now.

[OK-02] Connector startup timeout (30s) calling reject after worker may resolve
  The timeout in connector-runtime.js:180-188 races with the 'started'
  message. This is fine because Promise can only settle once — the second
  resolve/reject is silently ignored. Not ideal but not a bug.

[OK-03] assertInside() for agent file operations
  The path traversal check in register-agent-system-handlers.js:6-13
  looks like overprotection but is actually necessary — the renderer
  sends user-provided relativePath strings.


